                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">If you deal no damage to the mob, the charmed pet will take like 95% pct of the xp. Basically, it's a wasted kill.
<br />

<br />
If you deal 1 damage to a mob, or any amount you as a chanter can reasonably deal, you get 66% of full xp.
<br />

<br />
Now this is where I am a bit unsure - at some point, you deal enough damage to negate the xp penalty. I am not 100% sure of this, as it has never really been an issue for me, but I believe that if you (or your group) deal somewhere in the area of 50-66% of the damage, you get full xp. It is also a sliding scale, so dealing half of the "required damage for full xp" amount will give you 83% xp, etc.
<br />

<br />
Once your pet is no longer your pet, all damage it has dealt to a mob is forgotten by the xp calculator. That means, if you invis just before both mobs die, then nuke them to death, you get full xp for both. This is rather mana instensive though, more on that below.
<br />

<br />
For groups, the rules are the same as for single kills, but of course your groups deals a lot more damage so the xp penalty is usually negated. I believe the purpose of the new formula introduced around february was to make a balanced group easily outdamage the xp penalty, so I think it's rarely a problem in a 5-6 person group. The exact percentage of the damage needed, I am not sure of still.
<br />

<br />
For charming tactics, there are mainly two schools on how to treat your pet. One of them regards it as a temporary damage source that can be broken and nuked for full xp once it has done it's duty, and the other treats it as a regular longterm pet. With the first method, the one I have used the most, you will not give your pet any items, just haste it and balance it against the mobs so both your target and pet end up at low hp, then break (or for a slightly safer and easier route, let your pet kill the mob with low hp left (66%xp), then break to nuke your expet only(100%xp)). With the second method, you will usually equip your mobs with weapons to make it dualwield if it is able to, and perhaps even things such as summoned mage pet mask/armor. This method truly became viable with PoP mobs and their ability to regen to full in a matter of seconds if unaggrod. When they get low on hp, you simply break charm, mez them, and blur/re-mez until they forget you and regen to 100%, then tash and recharm. I normally only use this method in areas where:
<br />
a) Pets are in low supply
<br />
b) Certain NPCs become mad killing machines when used against his comrades.
<br />
c) Mob HP is so high that nuking isn't really an alternative unless below 2pct hp or so, which is too hard to time for the above break method. (haven't been to any such places myself, but I imagine EP charming falls under this)
<br />

<br />
Also, remember that haste + noslow is FAR better than nohaste + slow. You will kill a lot faster with the first method, breaks will be less frequent relative to your killing, and xp will fly in. The risk increases, but in most places you are charming that shouldn't be an issue anyway. Also remember we have a practically free 50% slow (Tepid Deeds) which is incredible for those times you dont need the absolute best one. With Haste + Tepid, and a bit of sitregen time between pulls, a mob can usually go through three of his own equals before getting so low you need to break and kill it, which will increase your efficiency - especially if you frequently find yourself low on mana. Charm and Nuke are the big mana hogs in a normal charm tactic, so the less you have to cast those spells, the better.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><center><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=2212" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://www.elerion.net/pics/sjhosig.jpg" border="0" /></a><span style="font-style: italic"><span style="font-size: 9px; line-height: normal">
<br />
"Carrot Cake Soup is like the taste of watching girls make out. It has an extraordinary power that oscillates between gentle and overwhelming, between light and dark, between pleasure and more pleasure." - Penny Arcade</span></span></center></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
